    "last_activity_date" : 1538257134,
    "last_edit_date" : 1538257134,
    "creation_date" : 1328126053,
    "answer_id" : 9102330,
    "question_id" : 9102318,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>A <code>Double</code> is not an <code>Integer</code>, so the cast won't work.  Note the difference between the <code>Double</code> <strong>class</strong> and the <code>double</code> <strong>primitive</strong>.  Also note that a <code>Double</code> is a <code>Number</code>, <a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/6/docs/api/java/lang/Number.html#intValue%28%29\" rel=\"noreferrer\">so it has the method</a> <code>intValue</code>, which you can use to get the value as a primitive <code>int</code>.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 262968,
      "reputation" : 790339,
      "user_id" : 548225,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 90,
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/iVKcbRoj.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "anubhava",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/548225/anubhava"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 595,
    "last_activity_date" : 1374086957,
    "last_edit_date" : 1374086957,
    "creation_date" : 1328126188,
    "answer_id" : 9102359,
    "question_id" : 9102318,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>You need to explicitly get the int value using method intValue() like this:</p>\n\n<pre><code>Double d = 5.25;\nInteger i = d.intValue(); // i becomes 5\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Or </p>\n\n<pre><code>double d = 5.25;\nint i = (int) d;\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 1021024,
      "reputation" : 4032,
      "user_id" : 1031372,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 80,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/327b0fc14f66878633ee3633a36d4889?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "OnResolve",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1031372/onresolve"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 3,
    "last_activity_date" : 1496613944,
    "last_edit_date" : 1496613944,
    "creation_date" : 1328126252,
    "answer_id" : 9102376,
    "question_id" : 9102318,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Double and Integer are wrapper classes for Java primitives for double and int respectively. You can cast between those, but you will lose the floating point. That is, 5.4 casted to an int will be 5. If you cast it back, it will be 5.0.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 309890,
      "reputation" : 14648,
      "user_id" : 622571,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/41523c6db74e0f187eae731a6871a320?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Richard Schwartz",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/622571/richard-schwartz"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 23,
    "last_activity_date" : 1328126424,
    "creation_date" : 1328126424,
    "answer_id" : 9102414,
    "question_id" : 9102318,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Like this:  </p>\n\n<pre><code>Double foo = 123.456;\nInteger bar = foo.intValue();\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
